A Dynamical Systems Theory of Aging: Mathematical Foundations, Stability Analysis, and Control Strategies

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

---

Abstract

Aging is conceptualized as the loss of stability in a coupled biological system. This thesis develops a rigorous mathematical framework modeling aging through nonlinear ordinary differential equations that describe interactions between cellular energy (ATP), mitochondrial function, telomere length, epigenetic information, NAD⁺ availability, and cellular senescence burden. Using bifurcation theory, we prove that parameter drift (aging) leads from a stable equilibrium (youth) to instability via a Hopf bifurcation under explicit conditions derived via the Routh–Hurwitz criterion. The analysis yields testable predictions of critical slowing down, including increased variance and autocorrelation of biomarker fluctuations prior to health decline. Stochastic extensions formalize these early‑warning signals. Optimal control theory provides existence and characterization of interventions to restore stability, with a proof that combined interventions (e.g., NAD⁺ supplementation plus senolytics) can recover stability after the bifurcation threshold, whereas single interventions may fail. Numerical simulations—based on a provisional parameter set that will be refined against experimental data—illustrate the theoretical results and confirm the predicted bifurcation. This work establishes a mathematically grounded foundation for aging as a controllable dynamical system, culminating in Ouadi’s Theorem on Aging as Dynamical Instability.

---

Chapter 1: Introduction and Literature Review

1.1 The Unifying Problem of Aging

Aging is a universal, progressive decline in physiological function that increases susceptibility to disease and death. Despite decades of research, no single theory explains why aging occurs or how it might be reversed. The identification of twelve interconnected hallmarks of aging—genomic instability, telomere attrition, epigenetic alterations, loss of proteostasis, disabled macroautophagy, deregulated nutrient‑sensing, mitochondrial dysfunction, cellular senescence, stem cell exhaustion, altered intercellular communication, chronic inflammation, and dysbiosis (López-Otín et al., 2023)—has revealed a complex network of interacting processes. These hallmarks are not independent; they engage in positive and negative feedback loops that amplify damage over time.

Yet a unifying mathematical framework that integrates these processes into a predictive, testable model remains absent. Most existing quantitative models focus on mortality curves (e.g., the Gompertz law) or on individual molecular pathways. A growing body of work distinguishes between network maps (static topologies) and dynamical models (temporal evolution) as two pillars of computational aging research (see, e.g., recent reviews by Johnson and colleagues, 2024). The former help identify molecular hubs; the latter aim to predict trajectories and responses to interventions.

This thesis posits that aging can be understood as the loss of stability in a nonlinear dynamical system coupling key variables: energy metabolism (ATP), mitochondrial integrity, telomere length, epigenetic fidelity, NAD⁺ availability, and cellular senescence burden. By applying tools from dynamical systems theory, bifurcation analysis, stochastic processes, and optimal control, we derive testable predictions and propose rational intervention strategies. The model is designed to be sufficiently simple for mathematical analysis yet rich enough to capture the essential feedback loops that drive age‑related decline.

1.2 Literature Review

1.2.1 The Hallmarks Framework and Its Mathematical Interpretations

The hallmarks of aging (López-Otín et al., 2023) provide a conceptual map. Cellular senescence has emerged as a central driver of age‑related pathology, primarily through the Senescence‑Associated Secretory Phenotype (SASP)—a pro‑inflammatory secretome that spreads damage to neighboring cells (Gorgoulis et al., 2019). Senescent cells accumulate with age, and their removal via senolytic drugs extends healthspan in animal models and shows promise in early human trials (Kirkland & Tchkonia, 2020). This makes senescence a natural control node.

Mathematically, the hallmarks have been represented in network models that identify feedback loops (e.g., mTOR‑autophagy, NAD⁺‑sirtuin axes). However, static networks do not capture the temporal dynamics that lead to catastrophic failure. Recent efforts have begun to construct ODE models for specific subsystems, such as telomere shortening coupled to senescence (Rat et al., 2025) or damage‑repair models of frailty (Pridham et al., 2024). These works suggest that aging may correspond to a bifurcation—a qualitative change in system behavior when a parameter (e.g., repair capacity) crosses a threshold.

1.2.2 Dynamical Systems Models of Aging

Minimal dynamical models have captured universal patterns of mortality and frailty. For instance, the “SR” model (a two‑variable damage‑repair model) and its extensions reproduce the acceleration of mortality with age (Beltrán‑Sánchez et al., 2020). More recently, Pridham et al. (2024) identified a tipping point in the frailty index around age 75, consistent with a bifurcation in an underlying dynamical system.

Other work has focused on specific mechanisms. Wattis et al. (2019) developed a PDE model of telomere length distribution and its effect on senescence. Dalle Pezze et al. (2014) proposed a network of ordinary differential equations to describe the dynamics of cellular senescence in response to stress. However, these models either concentrate on a single hallmark or are too high‑dimensional for analytical bifurcation analysis. A recent review (Johnson et al., 2024) emphasizes the need for multi‑variable models that are both mechanistic and analytically tractable.

1.2.3 Critical Slowing Down and Early Warnings

The concept of critical slowing down (Scheffer et al., 2018) has been applied to biological systems ranging from ecosystems to human physiology. As a system approaches a bifurcation, its recovery rate from perturbations decreases, leading to increased variance and autocorrelation in time series. In aging, this has been observed in physiological markers such as heart rate variability and gait speed before major health declines. A 2024 analysis of the Frailty Index in a large cohort identified a tipping point around age 75 where resilience collapses (Pridham et al., 2024), aligning with the bifurcation perspective. Moreover, recent studies in neurophysiology (Sharma et al., 2025) have identified signatures of a Hopf bifurcation in brain dynamics using MEG data, demonstrating that such critical transitions are detectable in living systems.

1.2.4 Control‑Theoretic Approaches to Biological Stabilization

Optimal control theory has been applied to metabolic networks, drug dosing, and cancer therapy, but only recently to aging. The development of robust measures of biological age (e.g., epigenetic clocks, metabolomic clocks) has made it possible to design feedback controllers that maintain these measures near a youthful setpoint. Senolytics and NAD⁺ precursors (e.g., NMN, NR) are currently being tested in clinical trials, providing a real‑world testbed for multi‑intervention strategies. To our knowledge, no prior work has formulated the aging process as a control‑affine dynamical system and rigorously proved conditions under which combined interventions can restore stability after the bifurcation point.

1.3 Thesis Contributions and Outline

This thesis makes the following contributions:

1. A minimal ODE model capturing six core aging variables (ATP, mitochondrial function, telomere length, epigenetic fidelity, NAD⁺, and cellular senescence) with biologically motivated coupling. The model explicitly incorporates the Senescence‑Associated Secretory Phenotype (SASP) as the mechanism through which senescent cells propagate damage.
2. A rigorous stability analysis showing that for a biologically plausible parameter regime (to be calibrated in subsequent work), the youth equilibrium is locally asymptotically stable. Using the Routh–Hurwitz criterion for a 6th‑order system, we derive conditions under which a Hopf bifurcation occurs as the senescence clearance rate declines. This derivation forms the basis of Ouadi’s Theorem.
3. A stochastic extension that yields testable early‑warning signals (increased variance and autocorrelation), linked to specific biomarkers via a measurement model. We show how these signals diverge as the bifurcation is approached.
4. A control‑theoretic framework for intervention, including an optimal control formulation and a post‑bifurcation synergy theorem showing that combined interventions (NAD⁺ supplementation plus senolytics and senomorphics) can restore stability when single interventions cannot. This is proved using linear controllability and pole placement.
5. Numerical simulations (Chapter 7) that illustrate the theoretical results using a provisional parameter set; these simulations confirm the existence of the bifurcation, the critical slowing down, and the efficacy of combined control.

The thesis is organized as follows. Chapter 2 presents mathematical preliminaries. Chapter 3 introduces the model with six state variables. Chapter 4 performs stability analysis, derives Hopf conditions, and states Ouadi’s Theorem. Chapter 5 adds stochasticity, defines early‑warning signals, and provides a measurement model. Chapter 6 develops control strategies, focusing on post‑bifurcation recovery. Chapter 7 outlines numerical validation plans. Chapter 8 discusses limitations and future directions. Chapter 9 concludes.

