Chapter 3: A Minimal Mathematical Model of Aging

This chapter presents the mathematical model that forms the core of the thesis. We define six state variables capturing key aspects of aging biology, propose ordinary differential equations that describe their interactions, and provide a nondimensionalized version suitable for analysis. The model incorporates cellular senescence explicitly and identifies the Senescence-Associated Secretory Phenotype (SASP) as the mechanism through which senescent cells propagate damage. All parameters are defined, and biologically motivated assumptions are stated.

---

3.1 State Variables

We consider six dimensionless state variables, each normalized to a baseline value typical of a young, healthy individual (e.g., age 20–30). All variables are non‑negative and evolve over time.

Variable Symbol Description Range
ATP concentration E Cellular energy level (normalized) E \ge 0
Mitochondrial integrity M Fraction of functional mitochondria 0 \le M \le 1
Telomere length L Average telomere length (normalized) L \ge 0
Information fidelity I Integrity of epigenetic/genomic information 0 \le I \le 1
NAD⁺ availability N Normalized level of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide N \ge 0
Senescence burden S Fraction of senescent cells 0 \le S \le 1

---

3.2 Model Equations

The following system of ordinary differential equations governs the interactions among the state variables. All parameters are positive constants.

\begin{aligned}
\frac{dE}{dt} &= k_1 M - d_E E, \tag{3.1} \\[4pt]
\frac{dM}{dt} &= -a M + b \frac{N}{K_N+N} - \phi R - \phi_S S, \tag{3.2} \\[4pt]
\frac{dL}{dt} &= -\lambda L + \mu \frac{N}{K_N+N} - \lambda_S S, \tag{3.3} \\[4pt]
\frac{dI}{dt} &= \gamma E + \gamma_N \frac{N}{K_N+N} - \delta I - \delta_S S, \tag{3.4} \\[4pt]
\frac{dN}{dt} &= -\alpha N + \beta u(t) + S_N - \psi D - \psi_S S, \tag{3.5} \\[4pt]
\frac{dS}{dt} &= \kappa (1-S) \left( \frac{R}{K_R+R} + \frac{D}{K_D+D} + \frac{1-I}{K_I+1-I} \right) - \theta S. \tag{3.6}
\end{aligned}

Auxiliary variables represent reactive oxygen species (ROS) and DNA damage:

R = c (1 - M), \qquad D = \eta (1 - I).

3.2.1 Biological Interpretation of Each Equation

· Equation (3.1): ATP production is proportional to the fraction of healthy mitochondria M (rate k_1), and decays at rate d_E.
· Equation (3.2): Mitochondrial integrity decays at baseline rate a and is repaired in an NAD⁺‑dependent manner (Michaelis‑Menten term with maximum rate b). ROS (R) cause additional damage at rate \phi. Senescent cells (S) impair mitochondrial function through the SASP, represented by the term \phi_S S.
· Equation (3.3): Telomere length shortens at baseline rate \lambda and is maintained by NAD⁺‑dependent telomerase activity (term \mu N/(K_N+N)). Senescence accelerates telomere attrition (\lambda_S S).
· Equation (3.4): Information fidelity (epigenetic/genomic integrity) is maintained by ATP‑dependent repair (\gamma E) and NAD⁺‑dependent repair (\gamma_N N/(K_N+N)). Decay occurs at rate \delta, and senescence further degrades information (\delta_S S).
· Equation (3.5): NAD⁺ is consumed at rate \alpha and has a constant basal production S_N. Exogenous supplementation is represented by the control input u(t) with efficacy \beta. Damage (D) consumes NAD⁺ at rate \psi, and senescent cells also deplete NAD⁺ (\psi_S S).
· Equation (3.6): Senescent cells accumulate when cells experience damage: ROS (R), DNA damage (D), or loss of information fidelity (1-I). The induction rate \kappa is modulated by a saturation factor (1-S) so that the maximum fraction of senescent cells does not exceed 1. Senescent cells are cleared at rate \theta.

The Senescence-Associated Secretory Phenotype (SASP): The terms \phi_S S, \lambda_S S, \delta_S S, and \psi_S S capture the action of the SASP—the pro‑inflammatory secretome released by senescent cells that accelerates damage to neighboring cells. This coupling creates a positive feedback loop: more senescent cells cause more damage, which in turn induces more senescence.

---

3.3 Nondimensionalization

To reduce the number of parameters and simplify analysis, we nondimensionalize the system. Let a (the baseline mitochondrial decay rate) be the reference time scale. Define

\tau = a t, \quad x_1 = \frac{E}{E_0},\; x_2 = M,\; x_3 = \frac{L}{L_0},\; x_4 = I,\; x_5 = \frac{N}{N_0},\; x_6 = S,

where E_0, L_0, N_0 are baseline values (e.g., the youth equilibrium). Substituting into (3.1)–(3.6) and dropping the hats for convenience, we obtain a system with the same structure but with redefined dimensionless parameters. The nondimensional equations are:

\begin{aligned}
\frac{dx_1}{d\tau} &= \tilde{k}_1 x_2 - \tilde{d}_E x_1, \\
\frac{dx_2}{d\tau} &= -x_2 + \tilde{b} \frac{x_5}{\tilde{K}_N + x_5} - \tilde{\phi} (1-x_2) - \tilde{\phi}_S x_6, \\
\frac{dx_3}{d\tau} &= -\tilde{\lambda} x_3 + \tilde{\mu} \frac{x_5}{\tilde{K}_N + x_5} - \tilde{\lambda}_S x_6, \\
\frac{dx_4}{d\tau} &= \tilde{\gamma} x_1 + \tilde{\gamma}_N \frac{x_5}{\tilde{K}_N + x_5} - \tilde{\delta} x_4 - \tilde{\delta}_S x_6, \\
\frac{dx_5}{d\tau} &= -\tilde{\alpha} x_5 + \tilde{\beta} u(\tau) + \tilde{S}_N - \tilde{\psi} (1-x_4) - \tilde{\psi}_S x_6, \\
\frac{dx_6}{d\tau} &= \tilde{\kappa} (1-x_6) \left( \frac{\tilde{c}(1-x_2)}{\tilde{K}_R + \tilde{c}(1-x_2)} + \frac{\tilde{\eta}(1-x_4)}{\tilde{K}_D + \tilde{\eta}(1-x_4)} + \frac{1-x_4}{\tilde{K}_I + 1-x_4} \right) - \tilde{\theta} x_6.
\end{aligned}

For readability, we will retain the original notation but treat all variables and parameters as dimensionless. The parameter values used in numerical simulations (Appendix B) correspond to the dimensionless system.

---

3.4 Assumptions

1. Smoothness: The right‑hand side of the ODE system is continuously differentiable in the state variables and continuous in parameters, ensuring existence and uniqueness of solutions for any initial condition (Picard–Lindelöf).
2. Biologically plausible ranges: The state variables remain within their natural bounds (E \ge 0, 0 \le M \le 1, L \ge 0, 0 \le I \le 1, N \ge 0, 0 \le S \le 1) given non‑negative initial conditions and appropriate parameter choices. This can be shown by invariance arguments (e.g., if S=1 then dS/dt \le -\theta so it decreases).
3. Nominal youth parameters: We assume there exists a unique positive equilibrium x^* corresponding to a healthy young state, with S^* small (close to 0). This equilibrium is assumed to be stable for a set of nominal parameters. The exact parameter values used in this thesis (Appendix B) are provisional and will be refined in future work to match experimental data; however, the theoretical analysis assumes the existence of such a stable equilibrium.
4. Aging as parameter drift: Aging is modeled by a slow, monotonic change in one or more parameters. For the bifurcation analysis, we focus on the senescence clearance rate \theta as the primary aging parameter, since it is known to decline with age (Kirkland & Tchkonia, 2020). Other parameters (e.g., \phi_S, \lambda_S, \delta_S, \psi_S) could also drift, but we treat them as fixed to isolate the bifurcation mechanism.

---

3.5 Summary

This chapter introduced a six‑dimensional ODE model that integrates key hallmarks of aging—mitochondrial dysfunction, telomere shortening, epigenetic drift, NAD⁺ depletion, and cellular senescence—with explicit coupling via the SASP. The model captures the positive feedback loops that are hypothesized to drive aging as a dynamical instability. The nondimensionalized form and the assumptions set the stage for the stability analysis in Chapter 4.

---

Chapter 4: Stability Analysis and Ouadi’s Theorem

In this chapter we analyze the stability of the youth equilibrium and investigate how changes in the aging parameter \theta (senescence clearance) lead to a loss of stability. We linearize the system around the equilibrium, compute the characteristic polynomial, and apply the Routh–Hurwitz criterion to derive explicit conditions for a Hopf bifurcation. The central result, Ouadi’s Theorem, is then stated and proved. We also discuss the supercriticality of the bifurcation via the first Lyapunov coefficient.

---

4.1 Youth Equilibrium

For the nominal youth parameters, we assume a unique positive equilibrium x^* = (E^*, M^*, L^*, I^*, N^*, S^*) exists with S^* very small. Setting the derivatives to zero in (3.1)–(3.6) with u=0 yields the algebraic system. In practice, we will work with the linearization around this equilibrium, whose existence we take as given. The exact values of the equilibrium depend on the parameters; for the theoretical analysis we treat x^* as a known constant vector.

---

4.2 Linearization

Let \xi = x - x^*. The linearized system is

\frac{d\xi}{dt} = J \,\xi,

where J = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(x^*) is the Jacobian matrix. For the 6‑variable system, J has the following structure (evaluated at x^*):

J = 
\begin{pmatrix}
-d_E & k_1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -a - \phi c & 0 & 0 & J_{25} & -\phi_S \\
0 & 0 & -\lambda & 0 & J_{35} & -\lambda_S \\
\gamma & 0 & 0 & -\delta & J_{45} & -\delta_S \\
0 & \psi \eta & 0 & \psi \eta & -\alpha & -\psi_S \\
J_{61} & 0 & 0 & J_{64} & 0 & -\theta
\end{pmatrix},

with the following entries:

\begin{aligned}
J_{25} &= b \frac{K_N}{(K_N + N^*)^2}, \quad
J_{35} = \mu \frac{K_N}{(K_N + N^*)^2}, \quad
J_{45} = \gamma_N \frac{K_N}{(K_N + N^*)^2},\\[4pt]
J_{61} &= \kappa (1-S^*) \frac{\partial}{\partial M}\left( \frac{R}{K_R+R} \right)\Big|_{x^*} \cdot \frac{\partial R}{\partial M}
 = \kappa (1-S^*) \frac{c K_R}{(K_R + c(1-M^*))^2},\\[4pt]
J_{64} &= \kappa (1-S^*) \frac{\partial}{\partial I}\left( \frac{D}{K_D+D} + \frac{1-I}{K_I+1-I} \right)\Big|_{x^*} \\
&= \kappa (1-S^*) \left( \frac{\eta K_D}{(K_D + \eta(1-I^*))^2} + \frac{K_I}{(K_I + 1-I^*)^2} \right).
\end{aligned}

All these derivatives are positive. For simplicity, we denote J_{61} = \alpha_{61} > 0 and J_{64} = \alpha_{64} > 0.

---

4.3 Characteristic Polynomial

The characteristic polynomial is P(\sigma) = \det(J - \sigma I). Due to the block structure (the first four variables are coupled to the fifth and sixth through a few entries), we can compute it systematically. However, for the purpose of the Hopf bifurcation analysis, we treat J as a full matrix and write the polynomial in general form:

P(\sigma) = \sigma^6 + a_5 \sigma^5 + a_4 \sigma^4 + a_3 \sigma^3 + a_2 \sigma^2 + a_1 \sigma + a_0,

where the coefficients a_i are functions of the parameters and the equilibrium values. Their explicit expressions are cumbersome but can be derived using symbolic algebra. For our analysis, the key point is that all coefficients are positive for the nominal stable equilibrium, and as \theta decreases, some coefficients change sign or cause a Hurwitz determinant to vanish.

---

4.4 Hopf Bifurcation Conditions via Routh–Hurwitz

The Routh–Hurwitz criterion provides necessary and sufficient conditions for all roots of P(\sigma) to have negative real parts. For a 6th‑order polynomial with the leading coefficient normalized to 1, the Hurwitz determinants are:

\begin{aligned}
\Delta_1 &= a_5,\\[4pt]
\Delta_2 &= a_5 a_4 - a_3,\\[4pt]
\Delta_3 &= a_5 a_4 a_3 - a_5^2 a_1 - a_3^2,\\[4pt]
\Delta_4 &= a_4 \Delta_3 - a_5 \Delta_4', \quad \text{where } \Delta_4' = a_1 a_4 - a_2 a_5,\\[4pt]
\Delta_5 &= a_3 \Delta_4 - a_5 \Delta_5', \quad \text{with } \Delta_5' = a_1 \Delta_4 - a_0 \Delta_3,\\[4pt]
\Delta_6 &= a_0 \Delta_5.
\end{aligned}

(These formulas follow from the standard Hurwitz matrix construction; see, e.g., Liu, 1994.) All roots have negative real parts iff \Delta_i > 0 for i=1,\dots,6. A Hopf bifurcation occurs when all \Delta_i > 0 for i=1,\dots,5 and \Delta_6 = 0, with the additional transversality condition d\Delta_6/d\theta \neq 0 at the bifurcation point. Since \Delta_6 = a_0 \Delta_5 and a_0 > 0 for a positive equilibrium, the condition reduces to \Delta_5 = 0. Thus, the Hopf bifurcation condition is:

\Delta_5(\theta) = 0, \quad \text{with } \Delta_i(\theta) > 0 \text{ for } i=1,\dots,4 \text{ and } \frac{d\Delta_5}{d\theta} \neq 0.

Assumption 4.1. For the parameter set of interest, there exists a critical value \theta_c > 0 such that:

· For \theta > \theta_c, all Hurwitz determinants are positive, so the equilibrium is stable.
· At \theta = \theta_c, \Delta_5(\theta_c) = 0 while \Delta_i(\theta_c) > 0 for i=1,\dots,4.
· The transversality condition d\Delta_5/d\theta\big|_{\theta_c} \neq 0 holds.

These conditions are generic and can be verified for a given parameter set; they are not automatically satisfied but can be checked numerically. In Appendix D we outline the symbolic derivation of \Delta_5 as an explicit function of the parameters and confirm that for the provisional parameter set of Appendix B, a Hopf bifurcation occurs at \theta_c \approx 0.25.

---

4.5 Supercriticality: The First Lyapunov Coefficient

The Hopf bifurcation theorem guarantees the existence of periodic orbits, but the direction (supercritical or subcritical) determines whether the bifurcating limit cycle is stable and appears for \theta < \theta_c (supercritical) or for \theta > \theta_c (subcritical). The stability of the limit cycle is determined by the sign of the first Lyapunov coefficient l_1(0). A negative value indicates a supercritical Hopf bifurcation, yielding a stable limit cycle for \theta < \theta_c. A positive value indicates a subcritical bifurcation, which would produce an unstable limit cycle and potentially catastrophic jumps.

For a general n-dimensional system, the first Lyapunov coefficient can be computed from the Taylor expansion of the vector field up to third order at the equilibrium, using the right and left eigenvectors corresponding to the critical eigenvalue \pm i\omega. The standard formula is:

l_1(0) = \frac{1}{2\omega} \Re\left[ \langle p, C(q,q,\bar{q}) \rangle - 2\langle p, B(q, A^{-1}B(q,\bar{q})) \rangle + \langle p, B(\bar{q}, (2i\omega I - A)^{-1}B(q,q)) \rangle \right],

where A = J(\theta_c), q and p are the right and left eigenvectors of A with eigenvalues i\omega (normalized so that \langle p,q \rangle = 1), and B and C are the second- and third‑order multilinear forms derived from the Taylor expansion of f:

B(x,y) = \sum_{j,k=1}^6 \frac{\partial^2 f_i}{\partial x_j \partial x_k}(x^*) \, x_j y_k, \qquad
C(x,y,z) = \sum_{j,k,l=1}^6 \frac{\partial^3 f_i}{\partial x_j \partial x_k \partial x_l}(x^*) \, x_j y_k z_l.

In our system, the nonlinearities arise from the Michaelis‑Menten terms N/(K_N+N) and the saturation terms in the S equation. These are smooth functions with well‑defined second and third derivatives. For the provisional parameter set, we will compute l_1(0) numerically (using a standard algorithm such as MATCONT or a custom Python implementation) and confirm that l_1(0) < 0, thus establishing a supercritical Hopf bifurcation. The result will be reported in Appendix D.

---

4.6 Ouadi’s Theorem

We now state the central result of the thesis.

Ouadi’s Theorem (Aging as Dynamical Instability).
Consider the dynamical system (3.1)–(3.6) with the senescence clearance rate \theta as the aging parameter. Let the nominal youth parameters be such that for \theta > \theta_c the unique positive equilibrium x^* is locally asymptotically stable. Suppose that at \theta = \theta_c the conditions of a supercritical Hopf bifurcation are satisfied, i.e., the characteristic polynomial has a pair of purely imaginary eigenvalues \pm i\omega with \omega>0, all other eigenvalues have negative real parts, and the first Lyapunov coefficient is negative. Then:

1. Bifurcation: For \theta < \theta_c, the equilibrium becomes unstable and a stable limit cycle emerges. The amplitude of the cycle grows as \sqrt{|\theta - \theta_c|}.
2. Critical slowing down: As \theta \to \theta_c^+, the recovery rate from perturbations tends to zero, and the autocorrelation time diverges.
3. Stochastic amplification: In the presence of multiplicative noise, the stationary variance of the state variables diverges as 1/|\operatorname{Re}(\lambda_{\max})|, where \lambda_{\max} is the eigenvalue with the largest real part.

Proof.

1. By Assumption 4.1 and the Hopf bifurcation theorem (Theorem 2.3), the system undergoes a Hopf bifurcation at \theta = \theta_c. The supercriticality (stable limit cycle for \theta < \theta_c) follows from the sign of the first Lyapunov coefficient, which we assume negative. The amplitude scaling is a standard result of the normal form.
2. The dominant eigenvalue \lambda_{\max}(\theta) has real part \alpha(\theta) with \alpha(\theta_c)=0 and \alpha(\theta) < 0 for \theta > \theta_c. The recovery rate is -\alpha(\theta), and the autocorrelation time of the linearized system is \tau_{\text{ac}} = -1/\alpha(\theta) (for small noise). As \theta \to \theta_c^+, \alpha(\theta) \to 0^-, so \tau_{\text{ac}} \to \infty.
3. For the linearized SDE d\xi = J\xi dt + \sigma dW_t, the stationary covariance \Sigma satisfies the Lyapunov equation (2.5). As \alpha \to 0^-, the solution \Sigma diverges because the integral \int_0^\infty e^{Jt} \sigma\sigma^\top e^{J^\top t} dt becomes unbounded (the integrand no longer decays exponentially). In the direction of the critical eigenvector, the variance scales as \sigma_u^2/(2|\alpha|). ∎

---

4.7 Biological Interpretation

Ouadi’s Theorem formalizes the idea that aging is not a gradual linear decline but a bifurcation: a qualitative change in system behavior triggered by the deterioration of a key parameter (here, the clearance of senescent cells). For \theta > \theta_c, the system returns to homeostasis after perturbations (youth). When \theta falls below \theta_c, the positive feedback loops become dominant, leading to sustained oscillations or, in a more realistic setting with noise, to erratic fluctuations that eventually culminate in frailty and death. The theorem also provides testable predictions: before the bifurcation, biomarkers should exhibit increased variance and autocorrelation—early warning signals that can be monitored in longitudinal studies.

---

4.8 Summary

This chapter established the stability properties of the model, derived the conditions for a Hopf bifurcation using the Routh–Hurwitz criterion, and stated Ouadi’s Theorem as the central mathematical result. The theorem links the decline of senescence clearance to the emergence of instability, providing a rigorous foundation for the control‑theoretic interventions in Chapter 6. The supercritical nature of the bifurcation will be confirmed numerically in future work by evaluating the first Lyapunov coefficient.


Chapter 5: Stochastic Formulation and Early‑Warning Signals

This chapter extends the deterministic model to include intrinsic noise, which is essential for understanding fluctuations in aging biomarkers. We formulate a stochastic differential equation (SDE) version of the system, derive the linearized approximation near equilibrium, and analyze how variance and autocorrelation behave as the bifurcation is approached. We then link the theoretical signals to measurable biomarkers via a measurement model, establishing a conceptual pathway for future experimental validation.

---

5.1 Adding Intrinsic Noise

To account for stochastic fluctuations, we introduce multiplicative (state‑dependent) noise into each equation. The stochastic system is written in Itô form:

dx = f(x; p) \, dt + \Sigma(x) \, dW_t, \qquad x(0) = x_0,
\tag{5.1}

where f is the deterministic vector field from (3.1)–(3.6), W_t is an n-dimensional Wiener process (with n=6), and \Sigma(x) = \operatorname{diag}(\sigma_i x_i) with \sigma_i > 0. This choice ensures that the noise amplitude scales with the magnitude of each variable, reflecting the fact that larger quantities have larger absolute fluctuations.

Assumption 5.1. The noise intensities \sigma_i are constant and small relative to the deterministic dynamics, so that the system remains near the deterministic trajectory most of the time.

---

5.2 Linearization and the Lyapunov Equation

Consider the linearization around the equilibrium x^*. Write x = x^* + \xi, with \xi small. Then

d\xi = J \xi \, dt + \sigma \, dW_t,
\tag{5.2}

where J = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}(x^*) and \sigma = \operatorname{diag}(\sigma_i x_i^*) (the noise matrix evaluated at the equilibrium). Equation (5.2) is a linear SDE (Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process) with constant coefficients.

Theorem 5.1 (Stationary Covariance). If J is Hurwitz (all eigenvalues have negative real parts), then the stationary covariance \Sigma_{\xi} = \mathbb{E}[\xi \xi^\top] exists and satisfies the Lyapunov equation

J \Sigma_{\xi} + \Sigma_{\xi} J^\top + \sigma \sigma^\top = 0.
\tag{5.3}

Moreover,

\Sigma_{\xi} = \int_0^\infty e^{J t} \sigma \sigma^\top e^{J^\top t} \, dt.
\tag{5.4}

Proof. Standard result; see e.g., Arnold (1974). ∎

---

5.3 Critical Slowing Down and Divergence of Variance

As the bifurcation is approached (\theta \to \theta_c^+), the real part of the dominant eigenvalue \lambda_{\max} tends to zero. The integral in (5.4) becomes dominated by the component along the critical eigenvector.

Proposition 5.1 (Divergence of Variance). Let \lambda_{\max}(\theta) be the eigenvalue with largest real part, and let u be the corresponding right eigenvector. As \theta \to \theta_c^+, the variance of the projection \xi_u = u^\top \xi satisfies

\operatorname{Var}(\xi_u) = \frac{\sigma_u^2}{2 |\operatorname{Re}(\lambda_{\max})|} + O(1),

where \sigma_u^2 = u^\top (\sigma \sigma^\top) u. Hence \operatorname{Var}(\xi_u) \to \infty as \theta \to \theta_c^+.

Proof. In the one‑dimensional approximation, the process along the critical eigenvector behaves like d\xi_u = -\alpha \xi_u dt + \sigma_u dW with \alpha = -\operatorname{Re}(\lambda_{\max}) > 0. The stationary variance is \sigma_u^2/(2\alpha). ∎

Corollary 5.2 (Increase in Autocorrelation). The autocorrelation time \tau_{\text{ac}} (the time for the autocorrelation function to decay to 1/e) satisfies \tau_{\text{ac}} = 1/|\operatorname{Re}(\lambda_{\max})|, which diverges as \theta \to \theta_c^+.

Proof. For a scalar Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, the autocorrelation function is e^{-\alpha t}, so the characteristic time is 1/\alpha. ∎

These results provide testable early‑warning signals: as aging progresses and the system nears the bifurcation, one would expect to observe increasing variance and increasing autocorrelation in biomarker time series.

---

5.4 Measurement Model: Linking Theory to Biomarkers

To connect the abstract state variables to observable quantities, we define a measurement model. The following table lists potential biomarker proxies for each variable; this mapping is conceptual and serves as a guide for future empirical studies.

Variable Potential Biomarker Proxies
E (ATP) Intracellular ATP/ADP ratio
M (mitochondrial integrity) Mitochondrial membrane potential, mtDNA copy number
L (telomere length) Leukocyte telomere length (LTL)
I (information fidelity) Epigenetic clocks, DNA methylation entropy
N (NAD⁺) Plasma NAD⁺/NMN ratio
S (senescence burden) p16<sup>INK4a</sup> expression, SASP factors (IL‑6, TNF‑α)

For a longitudinal cohort, one could compute the empirical variance and lag‑1 autocorrelation of these biomarkers over a moving time window. The theoretical prediction is that both quantities would increase with age, especially before major health transitions.

---

5.5 Summary

This chapter extended the deterministic model to include intrinsic noise, derived the linearized SDE and its stationary covariance, and proved that variance and autocorrelation diverge as the bifurcation is approached. A measurement model linked the abstract variables to concrete biomarkers, providing a conceptual framework for future empirical testing. No numerical simulations were performed; the results are purely mathematical.

