Appendix D: Expression for the First Lyapunov Coefficient (Theoretical)

The first Lyapunov coefficient l_1(0) determines the direction of the Hopf bifurcation. It is given by

l_1(0) = \frac{1}{2\omega} \Re\left[ \langle p, C(q,q,\bar{q}) \rangle - 2\langle p, B(q, A^{-1}B(q,\bar{q})) \rangle + \langle p, B(\bar{q}, (2i\omega I - A)^{-1}B(q,q)) \rangle \right],

where:

· A = J(\theta_c) is the Jacobian at the bifurcation point,
· q and p are the right and left eigenvectors of A corresponding to the eigenvalue i\omega, normalized so that \langle p, q \rangle = 1,
· B and C are the second‑ and third‑order multilinear forms derived from the Taylor expansion of the vector field.

For the specific nonlinearities in the model (Michaelis–Menten and saturation functions), this coefficient can, in principle, be evaluated symbolically given a parameter set. The sign of l_1(0) determines whether the bifurcation is supercritical (l_1(0) < 0) or subcritical (l_1(0) > 0).

